Creating a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 requires several steps. You need to set up a bot user on the Discord developer portal, invite the bot to your server, and then write the bot's code using Node.js and Discord.js v14. Below, you'll find the steps to create a simple 'ban' slash command for your Discord bot.

### Step 1: Create a Bot User on Discord Developer Portal
1. Go to the Discord Developer Portal (https://discord.com/developers/applications) and log in.
2. Click the "New Application" button, give it a name, and create your application.
3. Go to the "Bot" tab and click "Add Bot".
4. Under the "TOKEN" section, click "Copy" to copy your bot's token. You'll use this token in your bot code. Keep it secret!

### Step 2: Invite the Bot to Your Server
1. In the Discord Developer Portal, go to the "OAuth2" tab.
2. Under "URL Generator", select the "bot" checkbox under scopes.
3. Under "Bot Permissions", select the permissions your bot needs (for the ban command, you need to select "Ban Members").
4. Copy the generated URL and paste it into your browser to invite the bot to your server.

### Step 3: Set Up Your Project
1. Install Node.js from https://nodejs.org/
2. Create a new directory for your bot and initialize a new Node.js project by running `npm init`.
3. Install Discord.js v14 by running `npm install discord.js@14`.

### Step 4: Write the Bot Code
Here's a basic template for a Discord.js bot with a 'ban' command. Save this as `index.js` in your project directory.

```javascript
// Import required classes from discord.js
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, REST, Routes } = require('discord.js');
const { SlashCommandBuilder } = require('@discordjs/builders');

// Your bot's token
const token = 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN';

// Create a new client instance
const client = new Client({
  intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds, GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers, GatewayIntentBits.GuildBans],
});

// When the client is ready, run this code
client.once('ready', () => {
  console.log('Ready!');

  // Define a new slash command
  const commands = [
    new SlashCommandBuilder()
      .setName('ban')
      .setDescription('Bans a user from the server.')
      .addUserOption(option =>
        option.setName('user')
          .setDescription('The user to ban')
          .setRequired(true))
      .addStringOption(option =>
        option.setName('reason')
          .setDescription('The reason for the ban')
          .setRequired(false)),
  ].map(command => command.toJSON());

  // Register the slash command with Discord
  const rest = new REST({ version: '10' }).setToken(token);
  (async () => {
    try {
      console.log('Started refreshing application (/) commands.');

      await rest.put(
        Routes.applicationGuildCommands(client.user.id, 'YOUR_GUILD_ID'),
        { body: commands },
      );

      console.log('Successfully reloaded application (/) commands.');
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(error);
    }
  })();
});

// Respond to interaction commands
client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
  if (!interaction.isChatInputCommand()) return;

  const { commandName, options } = interaction;

  if (commandName === 'ban') {
    // The user executing the command must have the BAN_MEMBERS permission
    if (!interaction.member.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
      await interaction.reply({ content: 'You do not have permission to use this command.', ephemeral: true });
      return;
    }

    const user = options.getUser('user');
    const reason = options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

    // Ban the user
    try {
      const member = await interaction.guild.members.ban(user.id, { reason });

      await interaction.reply({ content: `Successfully banned ${user.tag} for the following reason: ${reason}` });
    } catch (error) {
      console.error(error);
      await interaction.reply({ content: 'There was an error trying to ban this user. Please check my permissions and try again.', ephemeral: true });
    }
  }
});

// Login to Discord with your client's token
client.login(token);
```

Replace `'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN'` with the token you copied from the Discord Developer Portal, and replace `'YOUR_GUILD_ID'` with your server's ID.

### Step 5: Running Your Bot
1. Open a terminal/command prompt in your project directory.
2. Run your bot code using Node.js by entering `node index.js`.

The bot should now start and print 'Ready!' in the console if everything is set up correctly. You should also see the new 'ban' command in the Discord server you've added your bot to. Note that it may take up to an hour for the command to show up on Discord due to caching.

Remember to handle errors and edge cases appropriately in your production bot for a robust application. The above code serves as a simplistic example and lacks comprehensive error handling, logging, and input validation for clarity and brevity purposes. In a production environment, all these aspects should be considered and implemented in your bot.

To create a C++ function that converts markdown formatted text to HTML, you can use a simple mapping of markdown elements to their corresponding HTML tags. This example will cover basic markdown elements such as headers, bold, italic, and links. For more complex markdown features, you might need a more sophisticated parsing library or approach.

Here's a basic implementation in C++:

```cpp
#include <string>
#include <sstream>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    std::stringstream ss(markdown);
    std::string line;

    while (std::getline(ss, line)) {
        size_t hashCount = 0;
        while (hashCount < line.size() && line[hashCount] == '#') {
            hashCount++;
        }

        if (hashCount > 0) {
            std::string header = line.substr(hashCount);
            std::string tag = "h" + std::to_string(hashCount);
            html += "<" + tag + ">" + header + "</" + tag + ">\n";
        } else {
            // Convert bold and italic
            for (size_t i = 0; i < line.size(); ++i) {
                if (line[i] == '*' || line[i] == '_') {
                    size_t start = line.find_first_of(line[i], 0);
                    size_t end = line.find_first_not_of(line[i], start + 1);
                    if (end == std::string::npos) end = line.size();

                    if (start + 1 < end) {
                        std::string text = line.substr(start + 1, end - start - 1);
                        if (line[start] == '*') {
                            html += "<strong>" + text + "</strong>";
                        } else {
                            html += "<em>" + text + "</em>";
                        }
                        i = end;
                    }
                } else {
                    html += line[i];
                }
            }
            html += "\n";
        }
    }

    return html;
}
```

### Explanation:
1. **Header Conversion**: The function checks for the number of leading `#` characters to determine the header level (e.g., `## Header` becomes `<h2>Header</h2>`).
2. **Bold and Italic Conversion**: It looks for `*` or `_` to identify bold (`**text**`) and italic (`_text_`) elements, respectively. It then wraps the text between these markers with the appropriate HTML tags (`<strong>` for bold and `<em>` for italic).
3. **Line Handling**: The function processes each line of the markdown text separately.

### Limitations:
- This function does not handle nested formatting (e.g., bold within italic).
- It does not support other markdown features like lists, blockquotes, code blocks, etc.
- It assumes that markdown formatting is correctly used (e.g., no unbalanced `*` or `_`).

For a more robust solution, consider using a dedicated markdown parsing library like `cmark` in C++.

